#Text=Chapter 47

#Text=“ I have been thinking it over again , Elizabeth , ” said her uncle , as they drove from the town ; “ and really , upon serious consideration , I am much more inclined than I was to judge as your eldest sister does on the matter .

#Text=It appears to me so very unlikely that any young man should form such a design against a girl who is by no means unprotected or friendless , and who was actually staying in his colonel 's family , that I am strongly inclined to hope the best .
#Text=Could he expect that her friends would not step forward ?
#Text=Could he expect to be noticed again by the regiment , after such an affront to Colonel Forster ?
#Text=His temptation is not adequate to the risk ! ”
#Text=“ Do you really think so ? ” cried Elizabeth , brightening up for a moment .
#Text=“ Upon my word , ” said Mrs. Gardiner , “ I begin to be of your uncle 's opinion .
#Text=It is really too great a violation of decency , honour , and interest , for him to be guilty of .
#Text=I cannot think so very ill of Wickham .
#Text=Can you yourself , Lizzy , so wholly give him up , as to believe him capable of it ? ”
#Text=“ Not , perhaps , of neglecting his own interest ; but of every other neglect I can believe him capable .
#Text=If , indeed , it should be so !
#Text=But I dare not hope it .
#Text=Why should they not go on to Scotland if that had been the case ? ”
#Text=“ In the first place , ” replied Mr. Gardiner , “ there is no absolute proof that they are not gone to Scotland . ”
#Text=“ Oh !
#Text=but their removing from the chaise into a hackney coach is such a presumption !
#Text=And , besides , no traces of them were to be found on the Barnet road . ”
#Text=“ Well , then -- supposing them to be in London .
#Text=They may be there , though for the purpose of concealment , for no more exceptional purpose .

#Text=It is not likely that money should be very abundant on either side ; and it might strike them that they could be more economically , though less expeditiously , married in London than in Scotland . ”
#Text=“ But why all this secrecy ?
#Text=Why any fear of detection ?
#Text=Why must their marriage be private ?
#Text=Oh , no , no -- this is not likely .
#Text=His most particular friend , you see by Jane 's account , was persuaded of his never intending to marry her .
#Text=Wickham will never marry a woman without some money .
#Text=He cannot afford it .
#Text=And what claims has Lydia -- what attraction has she beyond youth , health , and good humour that could make him , for her sake , forego every chance of benefiting himself by marrying well ?

#Text=As to what restraint the apprehensions of disgrace in the corps might throw on a dishonourable elopement with her , I am not able to judge ; for I know nothing of the effects that such a step might produce .
#Text=But as to your other objection , I am afraid it will hardly hold good .

#Text=Lydia has no brothers to step forward ; and he might imagine , from my father 's behaviour , from his indolence and the little attention he has ever seemed to give to what was going forward in his family , that he would do as little , and think as little about it , as any father could do , in such a matter . ”
#Text=“ But can you think that Lydia is so lost to everything but love of him as to consent to live with him on any terms other than marriage ? ”
#Text=“ It does seem , and it is most shocking indeed , ” replied Elizabeth , with tears in her eyes , “ that a sister 's sense of decency and virtue in such a point should admit of doubt .
#Text=But , really , I know not what to say .
#Text=Perhaps I am not doing her justice .

#Text=But she is very young ; she has never been taught to think on serious subjects ; and for the last half-year , nay , for a twelvemonth -- she has been given up to nothing but amusement and vanity .
#Text=She has been allowed to dispose of her time in the most idle and frivolous manner , and to adopt any opinions that came in her way .
#Text=Since the -- -- shire were first quartered in Meryton , nothing but love , flirtation , and officers have been in her head .
#Text=She has been doing everything in her power by thinking and talking on the subject , to give greater -- what shall I call it ?
#Text=susceptibility to her feelings ; which are naturally lively enough .
#Text=And we all know that Wickham has every charm of person and address that can captivate a woman . ”
#Text=“ But you see that Jane , ” said her aunt , “ does not think so very ill of Wickham as to believe him capable of the attempt . ”
#Text=“ Of whom does Jane ever think ill ?
#Text=And who is there , whatever might be their former conduct , that she would think capable of such an attempt , till it were proved against them ?
#Text=But Jane knows , as well as I do , what Wickham really is .
#Text=We both know that he has been profligate in every sense of the word ; that he has neither integrity nor honour ; that he is as false and deceitful as he is insinuating . ”
#Text=“ And do you really know all this ? ” cried Mrs. Gardiner , whose curiosity as to the mode of her intelligence was all alive .
#Text=“ I do indeed , ” replied Elizabeth , colouring .

#Text=“ I told you , the other day , of his infamous behaviour to Mr. Darcy ; and you yourself , when last at Longbourn , heard in what manner he spoke of the man who had behaved with such forbearance and liberality towards him .
#Text=And there are other circumstances which I am not at liberty -- which it is not worth while to relate ; but his lies about the whole Pemberley family are endless .
#Text=From what he said of Miss Darcy I was thoroughly prepared to see a proud , reserved , disagreeable girl .
#Text=Yet he knew to the contrary himself .
#Text=He must know that she was as amiable and unpretending as we have found her . ”
